#X text 497 312 One example is the feedback loop example we've seen before for frequency modulation feedback. We used [send~]/[receive~] but the principle is the same. In it \, the output of an oscillator control its frequency input. Hence \, the oscillator needs to be inserted in a feedback loop. In another example we also had a filter in the feedback loop \, let's check it again., f 45;
#X text 496 170 So why not just forget about [del.in~] and [del.out~] from ELSE \, as well as the native [delwrite~] \, [delread~] \, and [delreead4~] objects?, f 45;
#X text 50 542 There's also a [fbdelay2~] object that we'll see more in detail later when talking about flanging. You can check the help file for now. It is more related to the [ffdelay~] object as we get the delayed output and this output is then fedback to the input., f 54;
#X obj 361 622 fbdelay2~;
#X text 24 25 The [fbdelay~] object from ELSE is a feedback delay line just like the example from the last patch. By default the feedback index is not a multiplication factor \, but a decay time \, which is the time in ms that the input decays 60 dB (but it can be changed to a multiplication factor). Like [del.in~] \, it can resize the delay line and freeze it. Check the help file for more details.;
